(lldb) why What is the root cause of this crash? Walk through the program state, identify the defect, and propose a fix in code. Cover both a minimal local fix and a more thorough root-cause fix if they differ.
                                                                                
    Root‑cause analysis                                                         
                                                                                
     1 Location of the fault – The back‑trace points to line 12 of program.c,   
       inside the crc8 function:                                                
                                                                                
        crc ^= buf[i];                                                          
                                                                                
       This is the statement that accesses the input buffer.                    
     2 Buffer layout – In main the array buf is defined as                      
                                                                                
        uint8_t buf[7] = {0x01, 0x02, 0x03, 0x04, 0x05, 0x06, 0x07};            
                                                                                
       It therefore has exactly 7 bytes, with valid indices 0 … 6.              
     3 Call parameters – main invokes                                           
                                                                                
        crc8(buf, sizeof(buf));                                                 
                                                                                
       sizeof(buf) evaluates to the number of bytes in the array, i.e. 7.       
     4 Loop condition in crc8 – The function contains                           
                                                                                
        for (size_t i = 0; i <= len; i++) {                                     
            …                                                                   
        }                                                                       
                                                                                
       With len == 7, the loop executes for i = 0,1,2,…,7.                      
       The iteration with i == 7 attempts to read buf[7], which is one element  
       past the end of the array. That read overruns the stack‑allocated buf,   
       corrupting adjacent stack memory (e.g., other locals, saved frame        
       pointers, return address). The operating system detects this violation   
       and reports a stack buffer overflow, terminating the program.            
     5 Why it is a bug – CRC‑8 is supposed to process each byte of the input    
       exactly once. The algorithm’s semantics imply iterating over len bytes,  
       not len+1. The <= operator therefore introduces an off‑by‑one error      
       that turns a normal memory access into an out‑of‑bounds read.            
                                                                                
    Fixes                                                                       
                                                                                
     • Minimal local fix – Change the loop’s termination condition so it stops  
       before reaching len:                                                     
                                                                                
        for (size_t i = 0; i < len; i++) {   // <-- corrected                   
            crc ^= buf[i];                                                      
            for (int b = 0; b < 8; b++) {                                       
                crc = (crc & 0x80) ? (uint8_t)((crc << 1) ^ 0x07)               
                                     : (uint8_t)(crc << 1);                     
            }                                                                   
        }                                                                       
                                                                                
       This makes the function read only buf[0] through buf[len‑1], which       
       matches the intended processing of the buffer’s contents.                
     • More thorough root‑cause fix – In addition to the loop‑condition         
       change, adopt defensive programming practices to prevent similar         
       off‑by‑one bugs in other code:                                           
        • Pass the length explicitly (e.g., size_t nbytes) rather than relying  
          on sizeof on a pointer that may decay in other translation units.     
        • Assert that the length passed to crc8 does not exceed the actual      
          size of the buffer, e.g.:                                             
                                                                                
           assert(len <= sizeof(buf));                                          
                                                                                
          (only effective in debug builds; for production, consider a runtime   
          check).                                                               
        • Document that crc8 expects exactly len bytes and that the caller      
          must ensure len matches the buffer’s actual length.                   
        • If the function is used in multiple places, replace the raw array     
          with a struct or use explicit length arguments whenever the buffer    
          lives on the stack, reducing the chance of mismatched sizeof values.  
                                                                                
    Conclusion                                                                  
                                                                                
    The crash is caused by an off‑by‑one loop in crc8 that reads past the end   
    of a 7‑byte stack buffer. The immediate fix is to change the loop           
    condition from <= len to < len. A more robust solution adds explicit        
    length validation and avoids reliance on sizeof in call sites that may      
    move to other translation units.                                            
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
     • Apply the minimal fix: modify line 11 in crc8 to for (size_t i = 0; i <  
       len; ++i).                                                               
     • Implement the thorough fix by adding input validation and ensuring       
       callers always pass a length that accurately reflects the buffer’s       
       size, not just sizeof on a pointer. This prevents future overflows in    
       similar code.                                                            
                                                                                
